issue.body:
Related to #317: having code for visiting each node in a hierarchy might be nice. We have that code internally, and it seems like we could expose it. Protovis had [visitAfter](http://mbostock.github.com/protovis/jsdoc/symbols/pv.Dom.Node.html#visitAfter) and visitBefore methods. D3 doesn't require that hierarchy nodes implement any particular interface (for example, they can be loaded from static JSON files), so we'd probably want a method signature like this:

``` javascript
hierarchy.visitAfter(node, function(node, depth) {
  return stopVisiting;
});
```

There's no reason for this to be bound to a specific hierarchy layout instance, but making it a static method is more verbose. We took a similar approach with links.

body:
RickBullota independently suggests an optional nullable nodeSize property (originally elementSize) that when set would take priority over the current size property and switch to a fixed layout. It might work as follows:

``` js
d3_layout_treeVisitAfter(root, function(node) {
  if (nodeSize != null) {
    node.x = (node.x - x0) * nodeSize[0];
    node.y = node.depth * nodeSize[1];
  } else {
    node.x = (node.x - x0) / (x1 - x0) * size[0];
    node.y = node.depth / y1 * size[1];
  }
  delete node._tree;
});
```

The original suggestion of having individual dimensions be nullable is similar but a bit more flexible.

There's still a question of the origin, though. I'm guessing the root node should always be at the origin? Otherwise, you'd need to indicate what orientation of the tree you expect to determine a sensible center anchor for the root. Also, it's quite likely that when using fixed layout you'll still need to determine the computed full size of the tree, so as to size your container element (typically an SVG) appropriately. One way of doing this would be for setting layout.nodeSize to set size layout.size to the computed value automatically.

I ended up using a variation of Rick Bullota's implementation (which he explains in more detail [on the D3.js Google Group](https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!searchin/d3-js/element$20dynamic$20height/d3-js/7Js0dGrnyek/MfGJAdiPlQwJ)).

In my case, I wanted a custom node.x but wanted node.y to use the size value. My preference would be to have additional properties like sizeX, sizeY, nodeSizeX, and nodeSizeY, with something like this:

``` javascript
if (nodeSize != null) {
  node.x = (node.x - x0) * nodeSize[0];
  node.y = node.depth * nodeSize[1];
} else {
  if (nodeSizeX != null) {
    node.x = (node.x - x0) * nodeSizeX;
  } else if (sizeX != null) {
    node.x = (node.x - x0) / (x1 - x0) * sizeX;
  } else {
    node.x = (node.x - x0) / (x1 - x0) * size[0];
  }
  if (nodeSizeY != null) {
    node.y = node.depth * nodeSizeY;
  } else if (sizeY != null) {
    node.y = node.depth / y1 * sizeY;
  } else {
    node.y = node.depth / y1 * size[1];
  }
}
```

That should allow the fullest customization while still remaining backwards compatible. To fix the layout with specified node sizes, I specified a custom separation:

``` javascript
.separation(function (a,b) { return a.parent == b.parent ? 1 : 1 });
```

You can [see the result here](http://skillpedia.herokuapp.com/skills/6#big-picture).
